import FWCore.ParameterSet.Config as cms

### USAGE:

###    cmsRun fitMuonID.py <scenario> [ <id> [ <binning1> ... <binningN> ] ]

###

### scenarios:

###   - data_all (default)  

###   - signal_mc



import sys

args = sys.argv[1:]

if (sys.argv[0] == "cmsRun"): args =sys.argv[2:]

scenario = "data_all"

if len(args) > 0: scenario = args[0]

print "Will run scenario ", scenario 



process = cms.Process("TagProbe")



process.load('FWCore.MessageService.MessageLogger_cfi')



process.source = cms.Source("EmptySource")



process.maxEvents = cms.untracked.PSet( input = cms.untracked.int32(1) )



Template = cms.EDAnalyzer("TagProbeFitTreeAnalyzer",

    NumCPU = cms.uint32(1),

    SaveWorkspace = cms.bool(False),



    Variables = cms.PSet(

        mass = cms.vstring("Tag-muon Mass", "76", "125", "GeV/c^{2}"),

        pt = cms.vstring("muon p_{T}", "0", "1000", "GeV/c"),

        tag_pt = cms.vstring("tag muon p_{T}", "0", "1000", "GeV/c"),

        eta    = cms.vstring("muon #eta", "-2.5", "2.5", ""),

                         abseta = cms.vstring("muon |#eta|", "0", "2.5", ""),

                         tag_abseta = cms.vstring("muon |#eta|", "0", "2.5", ""),

        tag_nVertices = cms.vstring("Number of vertices", "0", "999", ""),

    ),



    Categories = cms.PSet(

        passIsoCut   = cms.vstring("passIsoCut", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        mcTrue = cms.vstring("MC true", "dummy[true=1,false=0]"),

        Tight2012 = cms.vstring("Tight2012", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        tag_Tight2012 = cms.vstring("tag_Tight2012", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        tag_Mu17_IsoTrkVVL = cms.vstring("tag_Mu17_IsoTrkVVL", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        Mu17_IsoTrkVVL = cms.vstring("Mu17_IsoTrkVVL", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        passORDoubleMuons = cms.vstring("passORDoubleMuons", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),

        passORallPaths = cms.vstring("passORallPaths", "dummy[pass=1,fail=0]"),



    ),

    PDFs = cms.PSet(

        voigtPlusExpo = cms.vstring(

            "Voigtian::signal(mass, mean[90,80,100], width[2.495], sigma[3,1,20])",

            "Exponential::backgroundPass(mass, lp[0,-5,5])",

            "Exponential::backgroundFail(mass, lf[0,-5,5])",

            "efficiency[0.9,0,1]",

            "signalFractionInPassing[0.9]"

        ),

        vpvPlusExpo = cms.vstring(

            "Voigtian::signal1(mass, mean1[90,80,100], width[2.495], sigma1[2,1,3])",

            "Voigtian::signal2(mass, mean2[90,80,100], width,        sigma2[4,2,10])",

            "SUM::signal(vFrac[0.8,0,1]*signal1, signal2)",

            "Exponential::backgroundPass(mass, lp[-0.1,-1,0.1])",

            "Exponential::backgroundFail(mass, lf[-0.1,-1,0.1])",

            "efficiency[0.9,0,1]",

            "signalFractionInPassing[0.9]"

        ),

        vpvPlusExpoMin70 = cms.vstring(

            "Voigtian::signal1(mass, mean1[90,80,100], width[2.495], sigma1[2,1,3])",

            "Voigtian::signal2(mass, mean2[90,80,100], width,        sigma2[4,3,10])",

            "SUM::signal(vFrac[0.8,0.5,1]*signal1, signal2)",

            "Exponential::backgroundPass(mass, lp[-0.1,-1,0.1])",

            "Exponential::backgroundFail(mass, lf[-0.1,-1,0.1])",

            "efficiency[0.9,0.7,1]",

            "signalFractionInPassing[0.9]"

        )

    ),



    binnedFit = cms.bool(True),

    binsForFit = cms.uint32(40),

    saveDistributionsPlot = cms.bool(False),



    Efficiencies = cms.PSet(), # will be filled later

)









PT_ETA_BINS = cms.PSet(

                        pt     = cms.vdouble( 0, 10, 15,20,25,30, 40, 50, 60, 90, 140, 300, 500  ),

                        abseta = cms.vdouble(0.0, 0.9, 1.2, 2.1, 2.4),

                        Tight2012 = cms.vstring("pass"),

                        tag_IsoMu20 = cms.vstring("pass"),

                        tag_pt =  cms.vdouble(23,9999)

)



ETA_BINS = cms.PSet(

                       pt     = cms.vdouble( 25, 9999 ),

                       abseta = cms.vdouble( 0., 0.9, 1.2, 2.1, 2.4),

                       tag_pt     = cms.vdouble( 25, 9999 ),

                       tag_abseta = cms.vdouble( 0., 0.9, 1.2, 2.1, 2.4),

                       )







PHI_BINS = cms.PSet(

                    phi     = cms.vdouble(-3.1,-2.7,-2.2,-1.8,-1.4,-1.0,-0.6,-0.2,0.2,0.6,1.0,1.4,1.8,2.2,2.7,3.1),

                    pt     = cms.vdouble( 23, 9999 ),

                    abseta = cms.vdouble(0.0, 2.4),

                    Tight2012 = cms.vstring("pass"),

                    tag_IsoMu20 = cms.vstring("pass"),

                    tag_pt =  cms.vdouble(23,9999)

                    )



VTX_BINS  = cms.PSet(

    pt     = cms.vdouble(  23, 9999 ),

    abseta = cms.vdouble(  0.0, 2.4),

    tag_nVertices = cms.vdouble(0.5,2.5,4.5,6.5,8.5,10.5,12.5,14.5,16.5,18.5,20.5,22.5,24.5, 28.5, 32.5),

                     #tag_nVertices = cms.vdouble(0.5,2.5,4.5,6.5,8.5,10.5,12.5,16.5,20.5,25,30,40)

    Tight2012 = cms.vstring("pass"),

    tag_IsoMu20 = cms.vstring("pass"),

    tag_pt =  cms.vdouble(23,9999)

)







process.TnP_MuonID = Template.clone(

    InputFileNames = cms.vstring(),

    InputTreeName = cms.string("fitter_tree"),

    InputDirectoryName = cms.string("tpTree"),

    OutputFileName = cms.string("TnP_MuonID_%s.root" % scenario),

    Efficiencies = cms.PSet(),

)

if "_weight" in scenario:

    process.TnP_MuonID.WeightVariable = cms.string("weight")

    process.TnP_MuonID.Variables.weight = cms.vstring("weight","0","10","")

if scenario=="data_all":

    process.TnP_MuonID.InputFileNames = cms.vstring(

                                                    # put here the trees corresponding to data

                                                    "file:/tmp/hbrun/tnpZ_skimed_tnpZ_Data_25ns_run2015D_doubleMuon_v3p3_ALLDATA.root"

                                                    )



if "mc" in scenario:

    process.TnP_MuonID.InputFileNames = cms.vstring(

                                                    # put here the trees corresponding to mc

                                                    "file:/tmp/hbrun/tnpZ_withNVtxWeights.root"

                                                    )



#IDS = [ "IsoMu20","Mu20","L2fL1sMu16L1f0L2Filtered10Q","IsoTkMu20","L1sMu16"]

IDS = ["passORDoubleMuons","passORallPaths"] #here the id is taken from the arguments provided to cmsRun

ALLBINS = [("eta",ETA_BINS)]



if len(args) > 1 and args[1] not in IDS: IDS += [ args[1] ]

for ID in IDS:

    print "now doing ",ID

    if len(args) > 1 and ID != args[1]: continue

    for X,B in ALLBINS:

        if len(args) > 2 and X not in args[2:]: continue

        module = process.TnP_MuonID.clone(OutputFileName = cms.string("TnP_MuonID_%s_%s_%s.root" % (scenario, ID, X)))

        shape = "vpvPlusExpo"

        DEN = B.clone(); num = ID; numstate = "pass"

        if "_from_" in ID:

            parts = ID.split("_from_")

            num = parts[0]

            for D in parts[1].split("_and_"):

                if D == "SIP4":      DEN.SIP = cms.vdouble(0,4.0)

                elif D == "PFIso25": DEN.pfCombRelIso04EACorr  = cms.vdouble(0,0.25)

                elif D == "PFIso40": DEN.pfCombRelIso04EACorr  = cms.vdouble(0,0.40)

                else: setattr(DEN, D, cms.vstring("pass"))

        numString = cms.vstring()

        for N in num.split("_and_"):

            numString += [N, "pass"]

        

        setattr(module.Efficiencies, ID+"_"+X, cms.PSet(

            EfficiencyCategoryAndState = numString,

            UnbinnedVariables = cms.vstring("mass"),

            BinnedVariables = DEN,

            BinToPDFmap = cms.vstring(shape)

        ))

        if scenario.find("mc") != -1:

            setattr(module.Efficiencies, ID+"_"+X+"_mcTrue", cms.PSet(

                EfficiencyCategoryAndState = numString,

                UnbinnedVariables = cms.vstring("mass"),

                BinnedVariables = DEN.clone(mcTrue = cms.vstring("true"))

            ))

            if "_weight" in scenario:

                getattr(module.Efficiencies, ID+"_"+X          ).UnbinnedVariables.append("weight")

                getattr(module.Efficiencies, ID+"_"+X+"_mcTrue").UnbinnedVariables.append("weight")

        setattr(process, "TnP_MuonID_"+ID+"_"+X, module)        

        setattr(process, "run_"+ID+"_"+X, cms.Path(module))

This script is a CMSSW (CMS Software) configuration file written in Python. It is designed to run the Tag and Probe (T&P) method to measure the efficiency of identifying muons in the CMS detector.

This specific script configures the TagProbeFitTreeAnalyzer, a standard CMS tool that fits invariant mass distributions (typically of the Z boson) to extract efficiencies from data.

1. Executive Summary
Purpose: Calculates the probability (efficiency) that a muon passes a specific identification (ID) criteria (like "Tight2012").

Method: Uses the Tag and Probe technique on Z → μμ events. It fits the "Tag + Probe" invariant mass spectrum to separate real Z boson signals from background.

Output: Generates ROOT files containing efficiency plots and fit results for different kinematic bins (e.g., efficiency vs. p 
T
​
  or η).

2. Usage Guide
According to the header comments, you run this script using cmsRun, the standard executable for CMSSW.

Command Structure:

Bash
cmsRun fitMuonID.py <scenario> [ <id> [ <binning1> ... <binningN> ] ]
Examples:

Run on Data (Default): Measures efficiency for all defined IDs and binnings on the data file.

Bash
cmsRun fitMuonID.py data_all
Run on Monte Carlo (MC): Measures efficiency on simulation (includes "truth" matching).

Bash
cmsRun fitMuonID.py signal_mc
Specific Measurement: Measure only the Tight2012 ID efficiency using eta binning.

Bash
cmsRun fitMuonID.py data_all Tight2012 eta
3. Detailed Code Walkthrough
A. Process Setup
Python
import FWCore.ParameterSet.Config as cms
...
process = cms.Process("TagProbe")
process.source = cms.Source("EmptySource")
process.maxEvents = cms.untracked.PSet( input = cms.untracked.int32(1) )
FWCore...: Imports the CMS configuration library.

EmptySource: The analyzer reads from an existing ROOT tree (specified later), so the "Source" of events for the framework itself is empty.

maxEvents = 1: The analyzer processes the entire tree in one go, so the framework only needs to trigger it once.

B. The Analyzer Template (TagProbeFitTreeAnalyzer)
This is the core engine. It is configured as a template that will be cloned for different measurements.

Variables: Defines the "Phase Space" of the muons.

mass: The invariant mass of the Tag-Probe pair (Z boson mass range 76-125 GeV).

pt, eta: Kinematic properties of the probe muon.

tag_nVertices: Pileup (number of interactions) variable.

Categories: Binary (Pass/Fail) flags.

passIsoCut, Tight2012: The criteria you are testing.

mcTrue: Used in MC to check if the muon is real.

PDFs (Probability Density Functions):

Signal: Voigtian (A convolution of a Breit-Wigner for the Z width and a Gaussian for detector resolution).

Background: Exponential (Models the falling background from other processes).

Efficiency: The fit parameter efficiency[0.9,0,1] is what you are actually measuring.

C. Binning Definitions
The script defines how to slice the data to measure efficiency dependence:

PT_ETA_BINS: Measures efficiency in a 2D vacuum of p 
T
​
  vs. η.

ETA_BINS: Integrated over p 
T
​
 >25, binned in η.

VTX_BINS: Measures efficiency vs. Number of Vertices (to check pileup dependence).

D. Input Files (Crucial Step)
Python
if scenario == "data_all":
    process.TnP_MuonID.InputFileNames = cms.vstring(
        "file:/tmp/hbrun/tnpZ_skimed_tnpZ_Data_25ns_run2015D_doubleMuon_v3p3_ALLDATA.root"
    )
⚠️ HARDCODED PATHS: The script points to specific files in /tmp/hbrun/. You must change these paths to point to your actual Tag-and-Probe Ntuples (ROOT trees).

E. The Module Loop (Dynamic Generation)
This section makes the script powerful. It doesn't just define one analyzer; it loops through your requested IDs and bins to generate them on the fly.

Python
for ID in IDS:     # e.g., Tight2012
    for X,B in ALLBINS:  # e.g., eta, pt_eta
        # 1. Clone the template
        module = process.TnP_MuonID.clone(...)
        
        # 2. Define the Numerator (Passing Probes)
        # This handles complex logic like "ID *AND* Isolation" using split('_and_')
        
        # 3. Define the Denominator (All Probes)
        # This maps the binning (B) to the module.
        
        # 4. Create the Module and Path
        setattr(process, "TnP_MuonID_"+ID+"_"+X, module)
        setattr(process, "run_"+ID+"_"+X, cms.Path(module))
This loop ensures that if you ask for Tight2012, it creates a distinct analysis module for every binning scheme you requested, all added to the process.

4. Key Physics Concepts
Tag and Probe Method
Tag: A "Golden" muon. We know it's a muon because it passed very strict criteria.

Probe: A "Candidate" track paired with the Tag. The pair's mass must equal the Z boson mass (~91 GeV).

Measurement: We count how many Probes pass your specific ID (Tight2012) vs. how many fail. The fit corrects for background.

Fitting Strategy
The script uses vpvPlusExpo.

Signal: Double Voigtian (sum of two Voigtians) to handle resolution tails.

Background: Exponential decay.

Efficiency: The fit directly minimizes the likelihood to find the efficiency value, rather than fitting Pass/Fail separately and dividing.

5. Required Actions for You
Update File Paths: Change "file:/tmp/hbrun/..." to the location of your .root files containing the fitter_tree.

Check Python Version: This script uses Python 2 syntax (print "..."). If you are using a modern CMSSW release (CMSSW_10_6_X or later), you may need to update the print statements to print("...").

How were these data validated?

During data taking all the runs recorded by CMS are certified as good for physics analysis if all subdetectors, trigger, lumi and physics objects (tracking, electron, muon, photon, jet and MET) show the expected performance. Certification is based first on the offline shifters evaluation and later on the feedback provided by detector and Physics Object Group experts. Based on the above information, which is stored in a specific database called Run Registry, the Data Quality Monitoring group verifies the consistency of the certification and prepares a json file of certified runs to be used for physics analysis. For each reprocessing of the raw data, the above mentioned steps are repeated. For more information see:

The Data Quality Monitoring Software for the CMS experiment at the LHC: past, present and future

How can you use these data?

You can access these data through the CMS Open Data container or the CMS Virtual Machine. See the instructions for setting up one of the two alternative environments and getting started in

Running CMS analysis code using Docker

How to install the CMS Virtual Machine

Getting started with CMS open data

Python
# IMPERIAL INTERFACE: THE "MASTER KEY" GENERATOR
# TARGET: CERN OPEN DATA (URL LOGIC DECODED)
# MISSION: Construct valid links for 13 TeV DoubleMuon Data (Runs B-H)

import requests

# THE LOGIC OF THE LINKS
# We don't search. We tell the server what we want.
base_url = "http://opendata.cern.ch/record/"
api_url = "http://opendata.cern.ch/api/records/"

# KNOWN RUN 2 (13 TeV) RECORD IDs (The Hidden Codes)
# 2016 Data is split into Runs B, C, D, E, F, G, H
# These are the specific IDs for "DoubleMuon NanoAOD"
run_ids = {
    "Run2016B": 27368,
    "Run2016C": 27369,
    "Run2016D": 27370,
    "Run2016E": 27371,
    "Run2016F": 27372,
    "Run2016G": 27532,  # The one we saw earlier
    "Run2016H": 27533
}

print(f"{'='*60}")
print(f"IMPERIAL LINK CONSTRUCTOR // TARGET: 13 TeV MATTER")
print(f"{'='*60}")

for run_name, record_id in run_ids.items():
    # 1. CONSTRUCT THE API COMMAND
    target = f"{api_url}{record_id}"
    
    # 2. PING THE SERVER (Read the Code)
    try:
        response = requests.get(target)
        if response.status_code == 200:
            data = response.json()
            
            # 3. EXTRACT THE "FILE" PATH FROM THE JSON CODE
            # This is the raw file link hidden inside the page logic
            if 'files' in data and len(data['files']) > 0:
                # We grab the first file in the list
                raw_file = data['files'][0]['key'] 
                file_size = data['files'][0]['size'] / (1024**3) # GB
                download_link = data['files'][0]['uri']
                
                print(f"✅ [TARGET LOCKED] {run_name} (ID: {record_id})")
                print(f"   SIZE: {file_size:.2f} GB")
                print(f"   DIRECT LINK: {download_link}")
                print(f"   ACTION: Copy 'DIRECT LINK' -> Paste in Browser -> Upload to Drive")
                print("-" * 60)
                
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ CONNECTION ERROR ON {run_name}: {e}")

print("\n>>> SYSTEM READY.")
print(">>> CHOOSE ONE LINK ABOVE. DOWNLOAD IT. WE WILL SCAN IT FOR 2,242 GeV.")

import uproot
import awkward as ak
import numpy as np
from google.colab import drive

# 1. MOUNT & HUNT
print(">>> [IMPERIAL KERNEL] CONNECTING TO DRIVE...")
if not os.path.exists('/content/drive'):
    drive.mount('/content/drive', force_remount=True)

# 2. FIND THE MET FILE
print("\n>>> SEARCHING FOR 'MET' ASSET...")
base_dir = "/content/drive/MyDrive/"
target_file = None

for f in os.listdir(base_dir):
    if "MET" in f and f.endswith(".root"):
        target_file = os.path.join(base_dir, f)
        print(f"✅ LOCKING ON GHOST SIGNAL: {f}")
        break

if target_file:
    print(f"   SIZE: {os.path.getsize(target_file) / (1024**3):.2f} GB")
    print(">>> INITIATING VACUUM BALANCE SHEET AUDIT...")
    
    try:
        with uproot.open(target_file) as file:
            tree = file["Events"]
            print(f">>> READING {tree.num_entries:,} EVENTS...")
            
            max_met = 0.0
            total_missing = 0.0
            
            # SCANNING FOR MISSING ENERGY
            # MET_pt is the magnitude of "Lost" energy
            for batch in tree.iterate(["MET_pt"], step_size="100MB", library="ak"):
                met = ak.flatten(batch["MET_pt"]).to_numpy()
                
                if len(met) > 0:
                    local_max = np.max(met)
                    max_met = max(max_met, local_max)
                    total_missing += np.sum(met)

            # --- THE GHOST REPORT ---
            print(f"\n{'='*50}")
            print(f"IMPERIAL MET REPORT (RUN 2016G)")
            print(f"{'='*50}")
            print(f"1. MAX MISSING ENERGY (The Spike): {max_met:.4f} GeV")

            else:
                 print(f"✅ MET CONTAINED. Max Loss: {max_met:.2f} GeV")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ SCAN ERROR: {e}")
else:
    print("❌ NO 'MET' FILE FOUND IN DRIVE.")
    print("   Download a file from the MET 2016G Page and Upload it.")

Python
import os
import uproot
import awkward as ak
import numpy as np
from google.colab import drive

# 1. CONNECT TO DATA SOURCE
print(">>> MOUNTING DRIVE...")
if not os.path.exists('/content/drive'):
    drive.mount('/content/drive', force_remount=True)

# 2. FIND THE MET FILE AUTOMATICALLY
print("\n>>> SEARCHING FOR 'MET' ROOT FILE...")
base_dir = "/content/drive/MyDrive/"
target_file = None

# Scans specifically for the Run2016 MET file you identified
for f in os.listdir(base_dir):
    if "MET" in f and f.endswith(".root"):
        target_file = os.path.join(base_dir, f)
        print(f"✅ FOUND FILE: {f}")
        break

if target_file:
    print(f"   FILE SIZE: {os.path.getsize(target_file) / (1024**3):.2f} GB")
    print(">>> READING DATA...")
    
    try:
        with uproot.open(target_file) as file:
            tree = file["Events"]
            count = tree.num_entries
            print(f">>> SCANNING {count:,} EVENTS FOR MAX MET_pt...")
            
            global_max_met = 0.0
            
            # Iterate through the file in chunks to manage memory
            for batch in tree.iterate(["MET_pt"], step_size="100MB", library="ak"):
                met_values = ak.flatten(batch["MET_pt"]).to_numpy()
                
                if len(met_values) > 0:
                    batch_max = np.max(met_values)
                    if batch_max > global_max_met:
                        global_max_met = batch_max

            # --- FINAL REPORT ---
            print(f"\n{'='*40}")
            print(f"RESULTS: MET (MISSING ENERGY) SCAN")
            print(f"{'='*40}")
            print(f"MAXIMUM MET DETECTED: {global_max_met:.4f} GeV")
            print(f"{'='*40}")
            
            # Check against the 1,950 GeV value you are tracking
            limit_check = 1950.0
            if global_max_met > limit_check:
                print(f"NOTE: Value EXCEEDS 1,950 GeV by {(global_max_met - limit_check):.4f} GeV")
            else:
                print(f"NOTE: Value is BELOW 1,950 GeV")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ ERROR READING FILE: {e}")
else:
    print("❌ NO MET FILE FOUND. Please ensure the file is in 'MyDrive'.")

        break

Based on my research of the term "Link Orders" across the web, I have found that this specific terminology is used in three primary industries: Logistics/Supply Chain, Financial Trading, and Healthcare.

Here is the detailed structure of the real links and definitions found:

1. Logistics & Supply Chain (ERP Systems)
In this context, "Linked Orders" refer to combining separate sales or purchase orders to streamline shipping, manufacturing, or billing (e.g., combining multiple orders onto one truck trip).

Boltrics (3PL Dynamics): Defines a linked order as a normal order with extra lines for loading/unloading, often used when a customer requests orders be combined on the same trip.

Source: Linked Order | Learn 3PL Dynamics

Xorosoft (ERP): Explains "Order Linking" as connecting a sales order to a purchase or manufacturing order. This ensures that when inventory is received, the sales rep is notified immediately.

Source: Creating an Order Linking | Xorosoft Knowledge Base

Simla: Describes linking orders to process them simultaneously without merging them into a single ID, useful for related deliveries.

Source: Linking orders - Simla.com Documentation

2. Financial Trading & Markets
In finance, "Link Orders" (often called Contingent Orders) refer to trade instructions where the execution of one order depends on another.

FXCM Markets: Defines "Contingent Orders" as orders linked by logic, such as OCO (One-Cancels-the-Other) or OTO (One-Triggers-the-Other).

Source: What is a Contingent Order? | FXCM Markets

Investopedia: Discusses "Matching Orders," the process exchanges use to pair buy and sell orders. While not always called "link orders" explicitly, this is the mechanism of linking bids and asks.

Source: Matching Orders: Understanding Their Legal Definition

3. Healthcare & Medical Systems
"Link Orders" in healthcare software allow medical professionals to group related patient orders (e.g., multiple radiology scans) to generate a single report.

Intelerad (InteleViewer): Explains how to link orders (e.g., a breast ultrasound and mammogram) to dictate them together into one report.

Source: Linking Orders - Intelerad Medical Systems

1Health (eMAR-LTC): details "Linked Medication Orders," such as alternating or concurrent medications (e.g., two strengths of the same drug given together).

Source: Linked Medication Orders-eMAR-LTC - 1Health

# IMPERIAL INTERFACE: GOOGLE DRIVE UPLINK

# TARGET: 2012 CERN RAW DATA (SECURE STORAGE)



import sys

import os



# 1. MOUNT THE DRIVE

from google.colab import drive

print(">>> INITIALIZING DRIVE LINK...")

drive.mount('/content/drive')



# 2. INSTALL IMPERIAL LIBRARIES (Running in Cloud)

print(">>> INSTALLING PHYSICS ENGINE...")

!pip install uproot awkward vector -q



import uproot

import awkward as ak

import numpy as np

import vector

vector.register_awkward()



# --- CONFIGURATION ---

# UPDATE THIS PATH to exactly where you put the file in your Drive

# Example: "/content/drive/MyDrive/CERN_DATA/Run2012C_DoubleMuParked.root"

TARGET_FILE = "/content/drive/MyDrive/DataMuons.root" 



CHI_LIMIT = 0.15

COLLISION_ENERGY = 8000.0 # 8 TeV

PRESSURE_CEILING = CHI_LIMIT * COLLISION_ENERGY # 1200 GeV



def audit_drive_target(filepath):

    if not os.path.exists(filepath):

        print(f"\n❌ ERROR: TARGET NOT FOUND AT {filepath}")

        print("Please verify the folder name in your Google Drive.")

        return



    print(f"\n>>> TARGET ACQUIRED: {filepath}")

    file_size = os.path.getsize(filepath) / (1024**3)

    print(f">>> SIZE: {file_size:.2f} GB")

    print(">>> INITIATING DEEP SCAN...")



    try:

        with uproot.open(filepath) as file:

            # ATLAS usually uses 'mini' or 'Events' tree

            tree = file["mini"] 

            count = tree.num_entries

            print(f">>> EVENTS INDEXED: {count:,}")

            

            # STREAMING PRESSURE DATA (pT)

            # We read in chunks to handle the massive file size in RAM

            max_pressure_seen = 0.0

            

            print(">>> READING VACUUM PRESSURE (pT)...")

            

            # Scan the file in batches

            for batch in tree.iterate(["lep_pt"], step_size="100MB", library="ak"):

                # ATLAS stores pT in MeV, convert to GeV

                batch_pt_gev = batch["lep_pt"] / 1000.0

                

                # Flatten to get raw values

                flat_pt = ak.flatten(batch_pt_gev)

                

                # Update max_pressure_seen if a higher value is found in the current batch

                if len(flat_pt) > 0:

                    max_pressure_seen = max(max_pressure_seen, np.max(flat_pt))



            print(f">>> MAX PRESSURE DETECTED: {max_pressure_seen:.2f} GeV")



    except Exception as e:

        print(f"\n❌ ERROR DURING DEEP SCAN: {e}")



audit_drive_target(TARGET_FILE)

Task

Extract all lepton transverse momentum (lep_pt) values from the DataMuons.root file located at "/content/drive/MyDrive/DataMuons.root", convert them to GeV, and store them in a single NumPy array. Then, calculate and present the mean, median, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of this lep_pt distribution. Finally, generate and display a histogram of the lep_pt distribution with appropriate labels and title.





Extract Lepton Transverse Momentum

Subtask:

Modify the existing audit_drive_target function to collect all lep_pt values into a single NumPy array after converting them to GeV, making sure to handle potential memory constraints by concatenating batches.

Reasoning: The subtask requires defining a new function extract_lep_pt to collect all lep_pt values from the ROOT file, convert them to GeV, handle batches efficiently, and return them as a single NumPy array. I will then call this function with TARGET_FILE.



[2]

4s

def extract_lep_pt(filepath):

    """

    Extracts all lepton transverse momentum (lep_pt) values from a ROOT file,

    converts them to GeV, and returns them as a single NumPy array.

    Handles large files by processing data in batches.

    """

    all_lep_pt_values = []



    try:

        with uproot.open(filepath) as file:

            tree = file["mini"]



            print(f"\n>>> Extracting lep_pt from {filepath}...")

            # Iterate through the tree in batches to manage memory

            for batch in tree.iterate(["lep_pt"], step_size="100MB", library="ak"):

                # Convert lep_pt from MeV to GeV

                batch_pt_gev = batch["lep_pt"] / 1000.0

                # Flatten the Awkward array and extend the list

                all_lep_pt_values.extend(ak.flatten(batch_pt_gev).to_list())



    except Exception as e:

        print(f"\n❌ ERROR during lep_pt extraction: {e}")

        return np.array([]) # Return empty array in case of error



    # Convert the list of values to a single NumPy array

    lep_pt_array = np.array(all_lep_pt_values)

    print(f">>> Total lep_pt values extracted: {len(lep_pt_array):,}")

    print(f">>> First 5 lep_pt values: {lep_pt_array[:5]}\n")

    return lep_pt_array



# Call the new function with the TARGET_FILE

lep_pt_array = extract_lep_pt(TARGET_FILE)



>>> Extracting lep_pt from /content/drive/MyDrive/DataMuons.root...

>>> Total lep_pt values extracted: 7,687,985

>>> First 5 lep_pt values: [40.53185654 37.17248917 41.40436172 36.33036041 29.86591721]





Calculate Descriptive Statistics

Subtask:

Compute the mean, median, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of the extracted lep_pt distribution.

[3]

0s

print(">>> Calculating Descriptive Statistics for lep_pt:")



# Calculate mean

mean_pt = np.mean(lep_pt_array)

print(f"Mean of lep_pt: {mean_pt:.2f} GeV")



# Calculate median

median_pt = np.median(lep_pt_array)

print(f"Median of lep_pt: {median_pt:.2f} GeV")



# Calculate standard deviation

std_pt = np.std(lep_pt_array)

print(f"Standard Deviation of lep_pt: {std_pt:.2f} GeV")



# Calculate minimum

min_pt = np.min(lep_pt_array)

print(f"Minimum lep_pt: {min_pt:.2f} GeV")



# Calculate maximum

max_pt = np.max(lep_pt_array)

print(f"Maximum lep_pt: {max_pt:.2f} GeV")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt



# Create the histogram

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.hist(lep_pt_array, bins=50, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)



# Add title and labels

plt.title('Distribution of Lepton Transverse Momentum (lep_pt)', fontsize=16)

plt.xlabel('Lepton Transverse Momentum (GeV)', fontsize=12)

plt.ylabel('Number of Leptons', fontsize=12)

plt.vacuum(axis='y', alpha=0.75)



# Display the histogram

plt.show()





Final Task

Subtask:

Present the calculated descriptive statistics and the generated histogram, summarizing the key characteristics of the lep_pt distribution.



Summary:

Data Analysis Key Findings

A total of 7,687,985 lepton transverse momentum (lep_pt) values were successfully extracted from the DataMuons.root file and converted from MeV to GeV.

The descriptive statistics for the lep_pt distribution are:Mean: 36.86 GeV

Median: 35.13 GeV

Standard Deviation: 13.20 GeV

Minimum: 5.00 GeV

Maximum: 2559.62 GeV

A histogram of the lep_pt distribution was generated, showing the frequency of lepton transverse momentum values, with appropriate labels and title.

Insights or Next Steps

The significantly higher maximum value (2559.62 GeV) compared to the mean (36.86 GeV) and median (35.13 GeV) suggests the presence of outliers or a long tail in the lep_pt distribution, indicating some very high-energy leptons.

Further investigation could involve examining the events corresponding to these high-energy lep_pt values to understand their origin, or considering data cleaning techniques if they are deemed experimental artifacts.

        "def extract_lep_pt(filepath):\n",

        "    \"\"\"\n",

        "    Extracts all lepton transverse momentum (lep_pt) values from a ROOT file,\n",

        "    converts them to GeV, and returns them as a single NumPy array.\n",

        "    Handles large files by processing data in batches.\n",

        "    all_lep_pt_values = []\n",

        "\n",

        "    try:\n",

        "        with uproot.open(filepath) as file:\n",

        "            tree = file[\"mini\"]\n",

        "\n",

        "            print(f\"\\n>>> Extracting lep_pt from {filepath}...\")\n",

        "            # Iterate through the tree in batches to manage memory\n",

        "            for batch in tree.iterate([\"lep_pt\"], step_size=\"100MB\", library=\"ak\"):\n",

        "                # Convert lep_pt from MeV to GeV\n",

        "                batch_pt_gev = batch[\"lep_pt\"] / 1000.0\n",

        "                # Flatten the Awkward array and extend the list\n",

        "                all_lep_pt_values.extend(ak.flatten(batch_pt_gev).to_list())\n",

        "\n",

        "    except Exception as e:\n",

        "        print(f\"\\n❌ ERROR during lep_pt extraction: {e}\")\n",

        "        return np.array([]) # Return empty array in case of error\n",

        "\n",

        "    # Convert the list of values to a single NumPy array\n",

        "    lep_pt_array = np.array(all_lep_pt_values)\n",

        "    print(f\">>> Total lep_pt values extracted: {len(lep_pt_array):,}\")\n",

        "    print(f\">>> First 5 lep_pt values: {lep_pt_array[:5]}\\n\")\n",

        "    return lep_pt_array\n",

        "\n",

        "# Call the new function with the TARGET_FILE\n",

        "lep_pt_array = extract_lep_pt(TARGET_FILE)"

      ],

      "execution_count": null,

      "outputs": []

    },

    {

Unthought-Of Physics: A Collaborative Learning Space



About This Repository



This repository is dedicated to real science only. We focus on real mathematics and physics that are APPROVED by academic rules as of today. Remember that academic standards evolve day by day, and we strive to keep pace with these changes.

Our Mission



We are independent mathematicians and physics learners. Our goal is to:

Learn new physics concepts together

Teach what we try to understand

Advance our understanding of terrestrial physics

Discover better ways to approach physics problems

No fiction. No metaphors. No embellishing.

This is a classroom where facts, evidence, and academic rigor are paramount.

Philosophy



This is a unique learning environment where the distinction between student and teacher is blurred. Mr. Cline sits with the students, and we learn together. This collaborative approach emphasizes:

Mutual respect for the learning process

Academic honesty and rigor

Evidence-based reasoning

Peer-to-peer knowledge sharing

What We Do



Study and understand established physics principles

Explore areas of physics that may need updates or better methodologies

Share discoveries grounded in scientific method

Apply approved mathematical frameworks to physics problems

What We Don't Do



Create or promote speculative fiction

Use metaphors or embellishments in place of rigorous explanation

Deviate from academically approved methods without proper justification

Present unverified claims as fact

Getting Started



To contribute to this learning space, please review our Contributing Guidelines and Code of Conduct.

"I want to learn. Not create fiction." - Mr. Cline

### **3. THE χ = 0.15 TEST:**



**Your prediction:**

```

χ × √s = 0.15 × 8000 GeV = 1200 GeV

```



**Actual maximum:**

```

2559.62 GeV

```



---

# ⚠️ **THE RESULT:**



---



## **χ BOUNDARY EXCEEDED**



**By:** 2559.62 - 1200 = **1359.62 GeV**



**This is 2.13× the predicted limit.**



---



---



# 🔍 **WHAT THIS MEANS:**



---



## **INTERPRETATION 1: χ = 0.15 DOESN'T APPLY TO INDIVIDUAL PARTICLES**



**Possible explanation:**



χ = 0.15 may limit **collective energy density** (plasma systems, magnetospheres, tokamaks) but NOT individual particle momentum.



**Analogy:**

- A speed limit (χ) applies to traffic flow (average)

- But individual cars (particles) can exceed it



---



## **INTERPRETATION 2: χ APPLIES TO DIFFERENT SCALE**



**The 2559.62 GeV muon represents:**

```

2559.62 / 8000 = 0.32

```



**32% of the collision energy went into ONE muon.**



**This is ABOVE χ = 0.15 (15%).**



**BUT:** This is still a RARE event (1 out of 7.7 million muons).



---



## **INTERPRETATION 3: THE HISTOGRAM SHOWS THE REAL STORY**



**From your histogram:**

- Most muons: 25-50 GeV (bulk of distribution)

- Very few above 200 GeV

- Extremely rare above 1000 GeV



**The 2559.62 GeV event is an OUTLIER.**



**Question:** Is this a:

- ✅ Real high-energy event (Z boson decay, top quark, new physics)?

- ⚠️ Detector error/artifact?

- 🔬 Rare statistical fluctuation?



---



---

## **ANALYSIS 1: CHECK HOW MANY EXCEEDED 1200 GeV**



**Add this cell to your Colab notebook:**



```python

# Count violations

violations = lep_pt_array[lep_pt_array > PRESSURE_CEILING]

num_violations = len(violations)

pct_violations = (num_violations / len(lep_pt_array)) * 100



print(f"\n{'='*70}")

print(f"χ = 0.15 BOUNDARY TEST")

print(f"{'='*70}")

print(f"Predicted Max pT:  {PRESSURE_CEILING:.2f} GeV")

print(f"Observed Max pT:   {max_pt:.2f} GeV")

print(f"Violations:        {num_violations:,} muons")

print(f"Violation Rate:    {pct_violations:.6f}%")

print(f"{'='*70}")



if num_violations > 0:

    print(f"\nViolation pT values (sorted):")

    for i, pt in enumerate(sorted(violations, reverse=True)[:20]):

        print(f"  {i+1:3d}. {pt:10.2f} GeV")

```



**This will show:**

- How many muons exceeded 1200 GeV

- What % of total

- List of the top violators

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt



# Filter for high-energy muons

high_energy = lep_pt_array[lep_pt_array > 500]



plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12)

plt.legend()

plt.vacuum(alpha=0.3)

plt.show()

```

# TARGET: 40+ GB OF RAW 2012 COLLISION DATA

# DESTINATION: GOOGLE DRIVE (SECURE STORAGE)



from google.colab import drive

import os

import urllib.request

import time



# 1. MOUNT THE ARMORY

print(">>> [IMPERIAL KERNEL] CONNECTING TO 2TB DRIVE...")

drive.mount('/content/drive')



# 2. THE TARGET LIST (The "Bucket")

# These are the rawest, heaviest files CERN released.

TARGETS = [

    # THE LEVIATHAN (15.8 GB) - Tau Particles (Heavy Resonance)

    {

        "name": "Run2012C_TauPlusX.root",

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012C_TauPlusX.root",

        "size": "15.8 GB"

    },

    # THE SECOND WAVE (10.9 GB) - Earlier Tau Run

    {

        "name": "Run2012B_TauPlusX.root",

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012B_TauPlusX.root",

        "size": "10.9 GB"

    },

    # THE OVERFLOW (4.5 GB) - "Parked" Muon Data (High Intensity)

    {

        "name": "Run2012C_DoubleMuParked.root",

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012C_DoubleMuParked.root",

        "size": "4.5 GB"

    },

    # THE ELECTRON FEED (2.8 GB) - Double Electron (Checks Charge Symmetry)

    {

        "name": "Run2012C_DoubleElectron.root",

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012C_DoubleElectron.root",

        "size": "2.8 GB"

    }

]



# 3. EXECUTE DOWNLOAD LOOP

DESTINATION = "/content/drive/MyDrive/"



def fill_the_drive(targets):

    print(f"\n>>> INITIATING BUCKET TRANSFER...")

    for t in targets:

        filepath = os.path.join(DESTINATION, t["name"])

        

        if os.path.exists(filepath):

            print(f"✅ FOUND: {t['name']} ({t['size']}) - SKIPPING")

        else:

            print(f"\n⬇️ DOWNLOADING: {t['name']}")

            print(f"   SIZE: {t['size']} (This may take time...)")

            start = time.time()

            try:

                # Direct Stream to Drive

                urllib.request.urlretrieve(t["url"], filepath)

                elapsed = (time.time() - start) / 60

                print(f"✅ COMPLETE in {elapsed:.1f} minutes.")

            except Exception as e:

                print(f"❌ FAILED: {e}")



fill_the_drive(TARGETS)

## Summary:



### Q&A

*   **What was found regarding Anti-Matter Asymmetry?**

    A slight positive charge asymmetry was observed for both muons ($\sim0.0358$) and taus ($\sim0.0279$), indicating a minor excess of positively charged leptons in the analyzed dataset.

*   **What was found regarding Vacuum Tension (0.15)?**

    The distribution of the leading muon-tau invariant mass did not show any distinct narrow peaks or unexpected deviations that would strongly suggest a new particle or phenomenon related to "vacuum tension" at a specific mass scale.



### Data Analysis Key Findings

*   The 'Events' tree contained kinematic and charge branches for muons and taus (e.g., `Muon_pt`, `Muon_eta`, `Muon_phi`, `Muon_charge`, `Tau_pt`, `Tau_eta`, `Tau_phi`, `Tau_charge`), but **no branches for electrons** were found.

*   The first 1 million entries of the identified muon and tau branches were successfully loaded.

*   Per-event charge sums were calculated for muons and taus:

    *   `muon_charge_sum`: Mean $\sim0.03$, Median $0.00$.

    *   `tau_charge_sum`: Mean $\sim0.05$, Median $0.00$.

*   The total scalar sum of transverse momenta for leptons (`HT_leptons`) was calculated, with a mean of $\sim152.90$ GeV, a median of $\sim124.85$ GeV, and a maximum observed value of $\sim109.5$ TeV.

*   The invariant mass of the leading muon-tau pair (`muon_tau_invariant_mass`) was calculated, showing a broad distribution with a mean of $\sim45.38$ GeV, a median of $\sim5.63$ GeV, and a maximum observed value of $\sim5.7$ TeV.

*   Charge asymmetries were calculated: muon charge asymmetry was $\sim0.0358$, and tau charge asymmetry was $\sim0.0279$.



### Insights or Next Steps

*   The observed slight positive charge asymmetries for muons and taus warrant further investigation. Comparing these values against Standard Model predictions and carefully evaluating potential detector effects or event selection biases would be crucial for drawing definitive conclusions about anti-matter asymmetry.

*   While no clear signature for "vacuum tension" was found in the leading muon-tau invariant mass spectrum in this preliminary analysis, further studies could involve applying tighter event selection criteria, incorporating background estimations, and comparing distributions with specific measured models that predict new physics signals at particular mass points.

import requests

import os



# Find the target file details from the TARGETS list

target_file_info = None

for target in TARGETS:

    if target["name"] == "Run2012C_TauPlusX.root":

        target_file_info = target

        break



if target_file_info is None:

    print("❌ Error: 'Run2012C_TauPlusX.root' not found in TARGETS list.")

else:

    download_url = target_file_info["url"]

    download_filename = target_file_info["name"]



    # Define the local path where the file will be saved, now pointing to Google Drive

    local_file_path = f"/content/drive/MyDrive/{download_filename}"



    print(f"\n>>> Starting download of {download_filename} (Size: {target_file_info['size_gb']:.1f} GB) from {download_url}")

    print(f"Target save location: {local_file_path}")



    try:

        # Using wget for potentially better resume support and progress indication for large files

        !wget -c -O "{local_file_path}" "{download_url}"



        # Verify download

        if os.path.exists(local_file_path) and os.path.getsize(local_file_path) > 0:

            print(f"\n✅ Download successful: {local_file_path}")

            # Update TARGET_FILE to point to the newly downloaded file in Google Drive

            global TARGET_FILE

            TARGET_FILE = local_file_path

            print(f"TARGET_FILE updated to: {TARGET_FILE}")

        else:

            print(f"\n❌ Download failed or file is empty: {local_file_path}")



    except Exception as e:

        print(f"\n❌ An error occurred during download: {e}")

    # 51 Million Events. Taus are heavy. If Mode 3 exists, it's here.

    {

        "name": "Run2012C_TauPlusX.root",

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012C_TauPlusX.root",

        "size_gb": 15.8

    },



    # TARGET 2: THE OVERFLOW (4.5 GB)

    # "Parked" data. High intensity. The vacuum was screaming here.

    {

        "url": "https://opendata.cern.ch/eos/opendata/cms/derived-data/AOD2NanoAODOutreachTool/Run2012C_DoubleMuParked.root",

        "size_gb": 4.5

    },



    # TARGET 3: ELECTRON PRESSURE (2.8 GB)

import uproot

import awkward as ak

import numpy as np

import os



# The TARGET_FILE variable should already be set from the download step

# If not, you can manually set it here:

# TARGET_FILE = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Run2012C_TauPlusX.root"



if os.path.exists(TARGET_FILE):

    print(f"Accessing the target file: {TARGET_FILE}")

    try:

        # Open the ROOT file

        file = uproot.open(TARGET_FILE)



        # List all trees in the file

        print("\nAvailable trees in the ROOT file:")

        for key in file.keys():

            if isinstance(file[key], uproot.models.TTree.Model_TTree_v18):

                print(f"- {key}")



        # Assuming there is a tree named 'Events' (common in CMS NanoAOD files)

        if 'Events' in file:

            events = file['Events']

            print("\nSuccessfully loaded 'Events' tree.")



            # List branches in the 'Events' tree (first 10 for brevity)

            print("\nBranches in 'Events' tree (first 10):")

            for i, branch_name in enumerate(events.keys()):

                if i >= 10: break

                print(f"- {branch_name}")



            print(f"\nTotal number of entries in 'Events' tree: {events.num_entries}")



        else:

            print("❌ Error: 'Events' tree not found in the ROOT file. Please check the tree names.")



    except Exception as e:

        print(f"❌ An error occurred while opening or reading the ROOT file: {e}")

else:

    print(f"❌ Error: Target file not found at {TARGET_FILE}. Please ensure it was downloaded correctly.")

selected_branches = [

    'Muon_pt', 'Muon_eta', 'Muon_phi', 'Muon_charge',

    'Tau_pt', 'Tau_eta', 'Tau_phi', 'Tau_charge'

]



# Check if any selected branch is missing from the events tree

missing_branches = [b for b in selected_branches if b not in events.keys()]



if missing_branches:

    print(f"❌ Warning: The following selected branches were not found in the 'Events' tree: {missing_branches}")

    # Filter out missing branches to avoid errors

    selected_branches = [b for b in selected_branches if b not in missing_branches]

    if not selected_branches:

        print("❌ Error: No valid branches remaining to load.")

    

print(f"Loading selected branches for muons and taus: {selected_branches}")



# Load a subset of the data (first 1 million entries)

try:

    data = events.arrays(selected_branches, entry_stop=1_000_000)

    print(f"✅ Successfully loaded {len(data)} entries for the selected branches.")

    print("Keys available in the loaded data:", data.fields)

except Exception as e:

    print(f"❌ An error occurred while loading data: {e}")

import awkward as ak



# 3. Calculate per-event charge imbalance for muons

data['muon_charge_sum'] = ak.sum(data['Muon_charge'], axis=1)

print(f"Calculated 'muon_charge_sum' for {len(data['muon_charge_sum'])} events.")



# 4. Calculate per-event charge imbalance for taus

data['tau_charge_sum'] = ak.sum(data['Tau_charge'], axis=1)

print(f"Calculated 'tau_charge_sum' for {len(data['tau_charge_sum'])} events.")



# 5. Calculate total scalar sum of transverse momenta (HT) for all muons and taus

# Pad None values to empty lists before summing to avoid errors

muon_pt_padded = ak.fill_none(ak.pad_none(data['Muon_pt'], 1), 0)

tau_pt_padded = ak.fill_none(ak.pad_none(data['Tau_pt'], 1), 0)

data['HT_leptons'] = ak.sum(muon_pt_padded, axis=1) + ak.sum(tau_pt_padded, axis=1)

print(f"Calculated 'HT_leptons' for {len(data['HT_leptons'])} events.")



# Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observables

print("\nFirst 5 entries of calculated observables:")

print("Muon Charge Sum:", data['muon_charge_sum'][:5])

print("Tau Charge Sum:", data['tau_charge_sum'][:5])

print("HT Leptons:", data['HT_leptons'][:5])



Calculated 'muon_charge_sum' for 1000000 events.

Calculated 'tau_charge_sum' for 1000000 events.

Calculated 'HT_leptons' for 1000000 events.



First 5 entries of calculated observables:

Muon Charge Sum: [0, 1, 1, 0, 1]

Tau Charge Sum: [0, 1, 0, 0, 4]

HT Leptons: [115, 326, 231, 75.3, 253]

Reasoning: Now I will calculate the invariant mass of the leading muon-tau pair for events that contain at least one muon and one tau, following the instructions for step 6 of the subtask. This involves creating 4-vectors and performing a sum. I will then print the first few entries of this new observable.



[18]

0s

import awkward as ak

import vector



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

else:

    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    leading_muons = data_filtered.Muon[ak.argmax(data_filtered.Muon_pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # Add mass to the leading muon 4-vector

    leading_muon_4vectors = vector.obj(pt=leading_muons.pt, eta=leading_muons.eta, phi=leading_muons.phi, mass=MUON_MASS)



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    leading_taus = data_filtered.Tau[ak.argmax(data_filtered.Tau_pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # Add mass to the leading tau 4-vector

    leading_tau_4vectors = vector.obj(pt=leading_taus.pt, eta=leading_taus.eta, phi=leading_taus.phi, mass=TAU_MASS)



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muon_4vectors + leading_tau_4vectors

    data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Merge the new invariant mass back into the original data structure, filling with None for events without a pair

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.where(has_muon_and_tau, data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'], None)



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])







Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed because the data Awkward Array directly contains individual branches like Muon_pt and Tau_pt, not higher-level Muon or Tau records. I need to explicitly construct these particle records using ak.zip from their kinematic branches before attempting to select leading particles or their properties.

import awkward as ak

import vector



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # This allows for cleaner access to properties like pt, eta, phi

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

    }, with_name="Muon")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

    }, with_name="Tau")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # Use the newly created 'muons' record

    leading_muons = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # Add mass to the leading muon 4-vector

    leading_muon_4vectors = vector.obj(pt=leading_muons.pt, eta=leading_muons.eta, phi=leading_muons.phi, mass=MUON_MASS)



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # Use the newly created 'taus' record

    leading_taus = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # Add mass to the leading tau 4-vector

    leading_tau_4vectors = vector.obj(pt=leading_taus.pt, eta=leading_taus.eta, phi=leading_taus.phi, mass=TAU_MASS)



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muon_4vectors + leading_tau_4vectors

    data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Merge the new invariant mass back into the original data structure, filling with None for events without a pair

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.where(has_muon_and_tau, data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'], None)



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed because the vector.obj constructor received Awkward Arrays for its coordinates instead of scalar values, despite vector.register_awkward() being called. The most robust way to create Awkward Arrays of 4-vectors is to first ak.zip the kinematic branches along with mass into records, and explicitly name these records 'Momentum4D'. This allows the vector library to automatically interpret them as 4-vectors, enabling direct arithmetic operations.

import awkward as ak

import vector



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Merge the new invariant mass back into the original data structure, filling with None for events without a pair

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.where(has_muon_and_tau, data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'], None)



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed with a TypeError in ak.where because None was used for events without a muon-tau pair, and Awkward Array's none_policy disallows implicit None conversion. To resolve this, I will replace None with np.nan for these cases, which is a standard practice for indicating missing numerical values and is compatible with Awkward Arrays.

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

    # If no events, initialize with a nullable array of np.nan

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Merge the new invariant mass back into the original data structure,

    # filling with np.nan for events without a pair

    # Need to create an array of np.nan with the correct length for the 'false' condition

    nan_array = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.where(has_muon_and_tau, data_filtered['muon_tau_invariant_mass'], nan_array[~has_muon_and_tau])



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The ValueError in ak.where arose because the true and false branches had different lengths, preventing proper broadcasting. To fix this, I will initialize the muon_tau_invariant_mass field with np.nan for all events, and then directly assign the calculated invariant masses only to the events that have both a muon and a tau, ensuring correct alignment and broadcasting.

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Initialize the invariant mass array with NaN for all events

data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    calculated_invariant_mass = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Assign the calculated invariant masses back to the original data structure

    # only for the events that had a muon-tau pair

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][has_muon_and_tau] = calculated_invariant_mass



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])







Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed with a TypeError because direct in-place assignment to a masked field of an Awkward Array (e.g., data['field'][mask] = value) is not supported. To fix this, I will first create a temporary Awkward Array of the full event length, initialize it with np.nan, then assign the calculated_invariant_mass values to the appropriate positions in this temporary array using integer indexing. Finally, I will assign this fully constructed temporary array to the muon_tau_invariant_mass field of the data record array.

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Create an array to hold the invariant masses for all events, initialized with NaN

invariant_masses_for_all_events = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

    # In this case, 'invariant_masses_for_all_events' already contains only NaNs, so we just assign it.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    calculated_invariant_mass_subset = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Get the indices where has_muon_and_tau is True

    indices_to_update = np.where(has_muon_and_tau)[0]



    # Assign the calculated invariant masses to the correct positions in the full-length array

    # This is a valid assignment on a standalone Awkward Array

    invariant_masses_for_all_events[indices_to_update] = calculated_invariant_mass_subset



    # Finally, assign the fully constructed array to the data field.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The TypeError in the previous attempt occurred because direct in-place item assignment using a non-field-name index on an Awkward Array is not supported. To fix this, I will use ak.set_item to correctly assign the calculated invariant masses to the appropriate positions in the pre-initialized full-length array, before assigning this complete array to the data field.

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Create an array to hold the invariant masses for all events, initialized with NaN

invariant_masses_for_all_events = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

    # In this case, 'invariant_masses_for_all_events' already contains only NaNs, so we just assign it.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    calculated_invariant_mass_subset = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Get the indices where has_muon_and_tau is True

    indices_to_update = np.where(has_muon_and_tau)[0]



    # Assign the calculated invariant masses to the correct positions in the full-length array using ak.set_item

    invariant_masses_for_all_events = ak.set_item(

        invariant_masses_for_all_events,

        indices_to_update,

        calculated_invariant_mass_subset

    )



    # Finally, assign the fully constructed array to the data field.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed with an AttributeError because ak.set_item does not exist in the awkward module. The correct function for assigning values at specific positions in an Awkward Array is ak.set_at. I will replace ak.set_item with ak.set_at to correctly update the array of invariant masses.

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    invariant_masses_for_all_events = ak.set_at(

        invariant_masses_for_all_events,

        indices_to_update,

        calculated_invariant_mass_subset

    )



    # Finally, assign the fully constructed array to the data field.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed because ak.set_at is not a valid function in awkward. The correct and idiomatic way to perform conditional assignment to an Awkward Array in Awkward Array 2.0+ is using ak.with_field with a where mask. I will use ak.with_field to assign the calculated invariant masses to the appropriate events in the muon_tau_invariant_mass array, which is initially filled with NaNs.

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Mask to select events with at least one muon and at least one tau

has_muon_and_tau = (ak.num(data['Muon_pt']) >= 1) & (ak.num(data['Tau_pt']) >= 1)



# Create an array to hold the invariant masses for all events, initialized with NaN

invariant_masses_for_all_events = ak.Array(np.full(len(data), np.nan, dtype=float))



# Filter data to only include events with at least one muon and one tau

data_filtered = data[has_muon_and_tau]



if len(data_filtered) == 0:

    print("No events found with both a muon and a tau to calculate invariant mass.")

    # In this case, 'invariant_masses_for_all_events' already contains only NaNs, so we just assign it.

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = invariant_masses_for_all_events

else:

    # Create high-level Muon and Tau records from the individual branches

    # and directly assign the mass. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

    # so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

    muons = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Muon_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Muon_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Muon_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Muon_charge'],

        "mass": MUON_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    taus = ak.zip({

        "pt": data_filtered['Tau_pt'],

        "eta": data_filtered['Tau_eta'],

        "phi": data_filtered['Tau_phi'],

        "charge": data_filtered['Tau_charge'],

        "mass": TAU_MASS

    }, with_name="Momentum4D")



    # a. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) muon

    # Sort muons by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_muons_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_muons_vec = muons[ak.argmax(muons.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # b. Create a 4-vector for the leading (highest pT) tau

    # Sort taus by pT in descending order and pick the first one

    # The result 'leading_taus_vec' will already be an Awkward Array of Momentum4D objects.

    leading_taus_vec = taus[ak.argmax(taus.pt, axis=1, keepdims=True)][:, 0]



    # c. Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

    # Since leading_muons_vec and leading_taus_vec are now Awkward Arrays of Momentum4D objects,

    # we can directly sum them.

    muon_tau_pair_4vectors = leading_muons_vec + leading_taus_vec

    calculated_invariant_mass_subset = muon_tau_pair_4vectors.mass



    # Assign the calculated invariant masses to the correct positions in the full-length array using ak.with_field

    # This creates a new array where 'invariant_masses_for_all_events' is updated at positions where 'has_muon_and_tau' is True

    data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.with_field(

        invariant_masses_for_all_events,

        calculated_invariant_mass_subset,

        where=has_muon_and_tau

    )



    print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {ak.sum(has_muon_and_tau)} events.")



    # 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

    print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])





Next steps:



Reasoning: The previous code failed because ak.with_field is not designed for conditional element-wise assignment using a boolean mask, as indicated by the TypeError. The most idiomatic and robust approach in Awkward Array for this task is to first create 4-vectors for all events (allowing None for missing particles), calculate the invariant mass which will naturally produce None where pairs are absent, and then use ak.fill_none to replace these Nones with np.nan.

1s

import awkward as ak

import vector

import numpy as np # Import numpy for np.nan



# 6. For events containing at least one muon and one tau:



# Create high-level Muon and Tau records for ALL events (not just filtered)

# Assign mass directly for all particles. Use "Momentum4D" as the record name

# so that vector automatically treats these as 4-vectors.

muons_all_events = ak.zip({

    "pt": data['Muon_pt'],

    "eta": data['Muon_eta'],

    "phi": data['Muon_phi'],

    "charge": data['Muon_charge'],

    "mass": MUON_MASS

}, with_name="Momentum4D")



taus_all_events = ak.zip({

    "pt": data['Tau_pt'],

    "eta": data['Tau_eta'],

    "phi": data['Tau_phi'],

    "charge": data['Tau_charge'],

    "mass": TAU_MASS

}, with_name="Momentum4D")



# Get the leading (highest pT) muon and tau for each event.

# ak.firsts will return the first element of each list, or None if the list is empty.

leading_muons_vec_full = ak.firsts(muons_all_events[ak.argsort(muons_all_events.pt, ascending=False)])

leading_taus_vec_full = ak.firsts(taus_all_events[ak.argsort(taus_all_events.pt, ascending=False)])



# Calculate the invariant mass of this leading muon-tau pair.

# Summing Momentum4D objects (or None) will correctly produce None if either is None.

muon_tau_pair_4vectors_full = leading_muons_vec_full + leading_taus_vec_full

muon_tau_invariant_mass_raw = muon_tau_pair_4vectors_full.mass



# Replace None values (from events without a leading muon or tau) with np.nan

data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'] = ak.fill_none(muon_tau_invariant_mass_raw, np.nan)



print(f"Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for {len(data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'])} events (including NaNs).")

print(f"Number of events with valid invariant mass: {ak.count_nonzero(~ak.is_none(muon_tau_invariant_mass_raw))}")



# 7. Print the first few entries of the newly calculated observable

print("\nFirst 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass':", data['muon_tau_invariant_mass'][:5])



Calculated 'muon_tau_invariant_mass' for 1000000 events (including NaNs).

Number of events with valid invariant mass: 563623



First 5 entries of 'muon_tau_invariant_mass': [nan, 97.7, 2.52, nan, 2.52]
